<choice>true</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
.</p>

<p>What must be true of the rate of cell division?  Can the cells continue to divide into two each day for the whole course of the pregnancy? 
</p>
<p>


<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>The model is wrong.  The rate of cell division must slow down dramatically.</choice>
<choice>The model is wrong.  The rate of cell division must slow down a little bit.</choice>
<choice>The model is wrong.  The rate of cell division must speed up a little bit.</choice>
<choice>The model is wrong.  The rate of cell division must speed up dramatically</choice>
<choice>The model is fine.  The rate of cell division can continue at the same speed.</choice>
<choice>The model is fine.  These calculations are irrelevant.</choice>
<choice>The model is fine.  Humans are just larger than we realize when being born.</choice>
<choice>The model is fine.  Scientists must have underestimated the number of atoms in the universe.</choice>
</choiceinput>
